The life cycle of an octopus

An octopus is a soft-bodied marine creature with eight arms called tentacles. They are invertebrates, the size of the smallest adult octopus is around 5 cm in length while the size of the largest octopus is around 6 meters in length.
Octopuses lay eggs after fertilization. The common octopus can lay more than ten thousand eggs.
The size of an egg measures up to 0.3 cm in length.

After 4 to 8 weeks of development, 
the larval octopus hatches. By the time baby octopuses begin hatching from their eggs, they are already orphans who must survive on their own.
In their early form, the octopuses stay at the surface of the ocean and get swept up in clouds of plankton, where they eat larval crabs, lobsters and starfish.
However, they run the risk of being devoured along with the plankton by other hungry sea life.
Mating, their form of reproducing, is a serious matter for the octopuses. The reason is that with two hundred thousand eggs laid, only 1% can survive and could reach adulthood.
Octopuses are one of several species that die after they mate or give birth. The male will seek multiple female mates.
Within months of mating with a female, the male will actually die. Consequently, males do not live as long in the wild as females do.
At this stage, the octopus begins to develop at a rapid pace. The weight of juvenile octopus is increased by 5% every day because of its constant feeding habits.
Within months of mating with a female, the male will actually die. Consequently, males do not live as long in the wild as females do.

This marks the end of the parents' purpose and the beginning of a new octopus life cycle.

The length of time that passes between hatching, reproduction and death varies among octopus species, and is between 2-5 years.
Females will carry the fertilized eggs with her until they grow enough to be released, usually in strings hanging around her den. This can last 2-10 months depending on the octopus species.
The end of the life cycle of a female mated octopus can be grim. Although they are very protective over their eggs, sit with them, and make sure that they are clean, the mother slowly wastes away.
